04423nam a22005535i 9780822384885DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223848857 a10.1515/97808223848852doi  a(DE-B1597)552447  a(OCoLC)1229160925  a(OCoLC)1167510569  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS480.45b.B586 2003 7aHIS0170002bisacsh1 aBose, Purnima, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOrganizing Empire :bIndividualism, Collective Agency, and India /cPurnima Bose. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource (292 p.) :b1 b&w photo  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments, -- tIntroduction -- t1. Rogue-Colonial Individualism: General Dyer, Colonial Masculinity, Intentionality, and the Amritsar Massacre -- t2. Feminist-Nationalist Individualism: Margaret Cousins, Activism, and Witnessing -- t3. Heroic-Nationalist Individualism: Kalpana Dutt, Gender, and the Bengali ''Terrorist'' Movement -- t4. Heroic-Colonial Individualism: Raj Nostalgia and the Recuperation of Colonial History -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOrganizing Empire critically examines how concepts of individualism functioned to support and resist British imperialism in India. Through readings of British colonial and Indian nationalist narratives that emerged in parliamentary debates, popular colonial histories, newsletters, memoirs, biographies, and novels, Purnima Bose investigates the ramifications of reducing collective activism to individual intentions. Paying particular attention to the construction of gender, she shows that ideas of individualism rhetorically and theoretically bind colonials, feminists, nationalists, and neocolonials to one another. She demonstrates how reliance on ideas of the individual-as scapegoat or hero-enabled colonial and neocolonial powers to deny the violence that they perpetrated. At the same time, she shows how analyses of the role of the individual provide a window into the dynamics and limitations of state formations and feminist and nationalist resistance movements.From a historically grounded, feminist perspective, Bose offers four case studies, each of which illuminates a distinct individualizing rhetorical strategy. She looks at the parliamentary debates on the Amritsar Massacre of 1919, in which several hundred unarmed Indian protesters were killed; Margaret Cousins's firsthand account of feminist organizing in Ireland and India; Kalpana Dutt's memoir of the Bengali terrorist movement of the 1930s, which was modeled in part on Irish anticolonial activity; and the popular histories generated by ex-colonial officials and their wives. Bringing to the fore the constraints that colonial domination placed upon agency and activism, Organizing Empire highlights the complexity of the multiple narratives that constitute British colonial history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aFeminismzIndiaxHistory. 0aIndividualismzIndiaxHistory. 0aNationalismzIndiaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822384885zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822384885423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822384885.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles